\"Kondor\"\n*OSN \"Yastreb\"<ref>[[:ru:\u042f\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431 (\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435)]]</ref>\n*OSN \"Berkut\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kamchatinfo.com/news/society/detail/2663/|title=\u0411\u043e\u0439\u0446\u044b \u043e\u0442\u0440\u044f\u0434\u0430 \"\u0411\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0442\" \u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u043c\u0447\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0432\u043b\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u044d\u043a\u043e\u0432. \u041a\u0410\u041c\u0427\u0410\u0422\u041a\u0410-\u0418\u041d\u0424\u041e\u0420\u041c.|date=24 March 2016|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324034158/http://kamchatinfo.com/news/society/detail/2663/|archive-date=24 March 2016}}</ref>\n*OSN \"Grif\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zakon-grif.ru/swat/memory/0.htm|title=\u0421\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u0438. \u041e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u0413\u0420\u0418\u0424\"|publisher=OSN \"Grif\" memorial page|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n*OSN \"Titan\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gorod48.ru/news/26360|title=\u0418\u0437 \u0427\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043b\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u044f\u0434 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430 \"\u0422\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\"|publisher=Gorod48.ru|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n*OSN \"Gepard\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vestnik-rm.ru/news-4-1910.htm|title=\u0412\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0438: \u0411\u043e\u0439\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430 \"\u0413\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0434\" \u0441\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0442 (\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0436)|publisher=The Mordovian Bulletin|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Saturn (detachment)|OSN Saturn]].\n\n==Spetsnaz units in other post-Soviet countries==\n\n===Ukrainian Spetsnaz===\n{{main|Special Forces of Ukraine}}\nLike all post-Soviet states, [[Ukraine]] inherited its Spetsnaz units from the remnants of the Soviet armed forces, GRU and KGB units. Ukraine now maintains its own Spetsnaz structure under the control of the Ministry of Interior, and under the Ministry of Defence, while the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] maintains its own Spetsnaz force, the [[Alpha Group (Ukraine)|Alpha group]]. The term \"Alpha\" is also used by many other post Soviet states such as Russia, Belarus, and Kazakhstan as these units are based on the Soviet Union's Alpha Group. Ukraine's [[Berkut (special police force)|Berkut special police force]] gained mainstream attention during the 2014 Ukrainian revolution as it was alleged to have been used by the government to quell the uprising. However, this is disputed as many officers were also wounded and killed in the action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/10/us-ukraine-killings-probe-special-report-idUSKCN0HZ0UH20141010|title=Special Report: Flaws found in Ukraine's probe of Maidan massacre|work=Reuters|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Belarusian Spetsnaz===\n{{main|5th Spetsnaz Brigade}}\nThe 5th Spetsnaz Brigade is a special forces brigade of the Armed Forces of Belarus, formerly part of the Soviet Spetsnaz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ww2.dk/new/army/gru/5obrsn.htm|title=5th independent Special Forces Brigade|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> In addition, the [[State Security Committee of the Republic of Belarus|State Security Committee (KGB)]] of Belarus that was formed from the inherited personnel and operators after the break up of the Soviet Union. KGB of Belarus has its own Spetsgruppa \"A\" (Alpha Group), which is the country's primary counter-terrorism unit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kgb.by/en/|title=The State Security Committee of the Republic of Belarus|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Kazakh Spetsnaz===\nAs with many post Soviet states, Kazakhstan adopted the term [[Alpha Group]] to be used by its special forces. The Almaty territorial unit of Alpha was turned into the special unit Arystan (meaning \"Lions\" in Kazakh) of the [[National Security Committee of the Republic of Kazakhstan|National Security Committee (KNB)]] of Kazakhstan.<ref>Mariya Y. Omelicheva, ''Counterterrorism Policies in Central Asia'', page 119.</ref> In 2006, five members of Arystan were arrested and charged with the kidnapping of the opposition politician [[Altynbek Sarsenbayuly]], his driver, and his bodyguard; the three victims were then allegedly delivered to the people who murdered them.<ref>[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-142419667/kazakh-security-officers-suspected.html Kazakh security officers suspected of kidnapping, not murdering oppositionist.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927105539/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-142419667/kazakh-security-officers-suspected.html|date=27 September 2013}}, BBC Monitoring International Reports, 22 February 2006.</ref>\n\nKokhzal (meaning wolf pack in Kazakh language) is a special forces unit of Kazakhstan responsible for carrying out anti terror operations as well as serving as a protection detail for the [[President of Kazakhstan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://military-kz.ucoz.org/publ/sovremennyj_kazakhstan/specpodrazdelenija_kazakhstana/specpodrazdelenija_rk_2007_god/14-1-0-80|publisher=Kazakh military site|title=SPECIAL FORCES OF KAZAKHSTAN (2007)}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe video game, ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege]]'' features five Spetsnaz operators named Glaz, Fuze, Kapkan, Tachanka, and Finka.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of special forces units]]\n*[[List of special police units]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[Viktor Suvorov]], ''[http://militera.lib.ru/research/suvorov6/  Spetsnaz]. The Story Behind the Soviet SAS'', 1987, Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-11961-8}}\n* David C. Isby, ''Weapons and Tactics of the Soviet Army'', Jane's Publishing Company Limited, London, 1988\n* Carey Schofield, ''The Russian Elite: Inside Spetsnaz and the Airborne Forces'', Greenhill, London, 1993\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Special forces of Russia}}\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://www.vvmvd.ru/ Official website of the Russian Interior Ministry special forces]\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://bratishka.ru/ Internet portal of Russian special forces]\n\n[[Category:Military of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Special forces of Russia]]\n[[Category:Special forces units and formations]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n[[Category:Army reconnaissance units and formations]]\n", "name_user": "Xero skills YT", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(I made improvements to the text)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spetsnaz"}
{"title_page": "Rhinns of Kells", "text_new": "[[File:RhinnsofKells.jpg|500px|thumb|Corserine and Carlin's Cairn from the trig point on Meaul.]]\n\nThe '''Rhinns of Kells''' are a range of hills in the [[Galloway Hills]] range, part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. The most easterly of  three parallel ridges, they are neighboured to the west by the [[Range of the Awful Hand]] and the [[Dungeon Hills]]. The eastern portion of the [[Minnigaff Hills]] range lies immediately southwest of the range. In total, these four ranges are part of the [[Galloway Forest Park]]. The ridge is located entirely within [[Dumfries and Galloway]], with the base of the western flanks being a western boundary of the county. \n\nAlthough distant, the ridge is paralleled to the east by the [[A713 road]]. This road provides access to the majority of the starting points for walking the ridge. Most commonly, these are Garryhorn Farm (the turnoff a few hundred metres north of [[Carsphairn]]) and Forrest Estate (accessed much further south a few kilometres north of [[St. John's Town of Dalry]]). Unclassified roads, one of which follows the [[Southern Upland Way]], and two others near [[Clatteringshaws Loch]] can be utilised, but are much less common due to the difficult terrain when ascending or descending from the south. <ref>Turnbull R. (2019) Walking the Galloway Hills: 35 Wild Mountain Walks Including the Merrick. Cicerone: Kendal.</ref> Due to the linear nature of the ridge, a full traverse will normally require two modes of transport at either end if to be walked in a day. Shorter, circular rounds from Forrest Lodge taking in the southern section of the ridge are, as a result, more popular. <ref>https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/galloway/corserine.shtml</ref> A bus service by Houston's Minicoaches runs from [[Dalmellington]] to [[Castle Douglas]] via Carsphairn and St. John's Town of Dalry multiple times a day. <ref>https://bustimes.org/services/520-dalmellington-castle-douglas</ref> \n\n===The Hills===\n------------------------------------\nThe hills of the range are the second highest of the Galloway Hills with the highest hill, Corserine, reaching 814m. The terrain is similar to that of the Range of the Awful Hand in that the walking is predominantly along flat grass with occasional boggy sections, however the drops to the west and east are high, steep and often craggy. The ridge south of Corserine, which is named the Rhinns of Kells on [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] maps - ignoring the northern portion, is notably rougher.\n\nFrom north to south (ignoring all satellite ridges other than [[Cairnsgarroch]]) the hills are: \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Summit !! Height (m) !! Listing <ref>http://www.hills-database.co.uk/database_notes.html#classification</ref>\n|-\n| Cullendoch Hill || 343 || Tu,3<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=13274</ref> ||\n|-\n| Craigencolon || 346 || Tu,3<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=13266</ref> ||\n|-\n| Black Craig || 528 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7185</ref> ||\n|-\n| Knockower || 511 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7188</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Coran of Portmark]] || 623 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1710</ref> ||\n|-\n| Bow || 613 || Tu,Sim,DT,GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1714</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Cairnsgarroch]] || 659 || Hu,Tu,Sim,D,GT,DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1705</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Meaul]] || 695 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1701</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Carlin's Cairn]] || 807 || Tu,Sim,D,sHu,CT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1690</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Corserine]] || 814 || [[Marilyn (hill)|Ma]],Hu,Tu,Sim,[[Corbett (hill)|C]],[[Donald (hill)|D]],DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1689</ref> ||\n|-\n| Millfire || 716 || DT,sSim<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1698</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Milldown]] || 738 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],sHu,GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1695</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Meikle Millyea]] || 748.64 || Hu,Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1693</ref> ||\n|-\n| Little Millyea || 578 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7174</ref> ||\n|-\n| Darrou || ''c.'' 470 || - ||\n|-\n|}\n\n===Ecology===\n--------------------------------\nThe range forms part of the Silver Flowe-Merrick Kells Biosphere Reserve, which incorporates a considerable portion of both ranges to the west and east, and is a [[Natura 2000]] site. <ref>https://eunis.eea.europa.eu/sites/UK0019841</ref> The area is very popular with invertebrates and swarms of [[Odonata]], [[Syrphidae]] and [[Lepidoptera]] during summer are common. <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver_Flowe-Merrick_Kells</ref> The main lochs attributed to the range are Loch Dungeon, Loch Minnoch and Loch Harrow, all on the east side and in close proximity. Loch Dungeon was known to historically contain [[Arctic Charr]] which died out due to acidification; [[Brown trout]] populations, however, survived and the water quality has improved. <ref>https://www.gallowayfisheriestrust.org/charr-Loch-Grannoch.php</ref> There are currently ten [[Osprey]] pairs known to nest in [[Dumfries and Galloway]]; these lochs are a known feeding ground. <ref>https://www.wwt.org.uk/wetland-centres/caerlaverock/experience/ospreys/#</ref><ref>http://www.gsabiosphere.org.uk/supporters/loch-doon-ospreys/</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\n--------------------------------\n'Rhinns' derives from the [[Old Irish]] ''rind'', later [[Ulster Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]] ''rinn'', meaning 'promontory' or 'point'. <ref>https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/rinn#Irish</ref> [[Kells, Dumfries and Galloway|'Kells']] is a parish in the historic county of [[Kirkcudbrightshire|Stewartry of Kirkcudbright]] to the southeast of the range near [[New Galloway]]. Its name possibly derives from the Old Irish ''cell'', later Irish and Scottish Gaelic ''cill'', meaning 'church', <ref>Blackie C (1887). A dictionary of place-names giving their derivations. Murray: London.</ref> but may instead be in reference to its heightened elevation or, historically, wooded land. <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kells,_Dumfries_and_Galloway</ref> Most of the hill names are of Scottish Gaelic or [[Scots language|Scots]] origin, such as Meikle (Scots: ''large'') Millyea (Scottish Gaelic: grey, round hill - ''meall liath''), which translates fully to 'large, grey, round hill'. <ref>https://www.screel.co.uk/walks/dumfries-galloway/the-rhinns-of-hell/</ref>\n\n===References===\n--------------------------------\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of the Southern Uplands]]\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of East Ayrshire]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:RhinnsofKells.jpg|500px|thumb]]\n\nThe '''Rhinns of Kells''' are a range of hills in the [[Galloway Hills]] range, part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. The most easterly of  three parallel ridges, they are neighboured to the west by the [[Range of the Awful Hand]] and the [[Dungeon Hills]]. The eastern portion of the [[Minnigaff Hills]] range lies immediately southwest of the range. In total, these four ranges are part of the [[Galloway Forest Park]]. The ridge is located entirely within [[Dumfries and Galloway]], with the base of the western flanks being a western boundary of the county. \n\nAlthough distant, the ridge is paralleled to the east by the [[A713 road]]. This road provides access to the majority of the starting points for walking the ridge. Most commonly, these are Garryhorn Farm (the turnoff a few hundred metres north of [[Carsphairn]]) and Forrest Estate (accessed much further south a few kilometres north of [[St. John's Town of Dalry]]). Unclassified roads, one of which follows the [[Southern Upland Way]], and two others near [[Clatteringshaws Loch]] can be utilised, but are much less common due to the difficult terrain when ascending or descending from the south. <ref>Turnbull R. (2019) Walking the Galloway Hills: 35 Wild Mountain Walks Including the Merrick. Cicerone: Kendal.</ref> Due to the linear nature of the ridge, a full traverse will normally require two modes of transport at either end if to be walked in a day. Shorter, circular rounds from Forrest Lodge taking in the southern section of the ridge are, as a result, more popular. <ref>https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/galloway/corserine.shtml</ref> A bus service by Houston's Minicoaches runs from [[Dalmellington]] to [[Castle Douglas]] via Carsphairn and St. John's Town of Dalry multiple times a day. <ref>https://bustimes.org/services/520-dalmellington-castle-douglas</ref> \n\n===The Hills===\n------------------------------------\nThe hills of the range are the second highest of the Galloway Hills with the highest hill, Corserine, reaching 814m. The terrain is similar to that of the Range of the Awful Hand in that the walking is predominantly along flat grass with occasional boggy sections, however the drops to the west and east are high, steep and often craggy. The ridge south of Corserine, which is named the Rhinns of Kells on [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] maps - ignoring the northern portion, is notably rougher.\n\nFrom north to south (ignoring all satellite ridges other than [[Cairnsgarroch]]) the hills are: \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Summit !! Height (m) !! Listing <ref>http://www.hills-database.co.uk/database_notes.html#classification</ref>\n|-\n| Cullendoch Hill || 343 || Tu,3<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=13274</ref> ||\n|-\n| Craigencolon || 346 || Tu,3<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=13266</ref> ||\n|-\n| Black Craig || 528 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7185</ref> ||\n|-\n| Knockower || 511 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7188</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Coran of Portmark]] || 623 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1710</ref> ||\n|-\n| Bow || 613 || Tu,Sim,DT,GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1714</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Cairnsgarroch]] || 659 || Hu,Tu,Sim,D,GT,DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1705</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Meaul]] || 695 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1701</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Carlin's Cairn]] || 807 || Tu,Sim,D,sHu,CT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1690</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Corserine]] || 814 || [[Marilyn (hill)|Ma]],Hu,Tu,Sim,[[Corbett (hill)|C]],[[Donald (hill)|D]],DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1689</ref> ||\n|-\n| Millfire || 716 || DT,sSim<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1698</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Milldown]] || 738 || Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],sHu,GT,DN<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1695</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Meikle Millyea]] || 748.64 || Hu,Tu,Sim,[[Donald (hill)|D]],GT,DN,Y<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1693</ref> ||\n|-\n| Little Millyea || 578 || Tu,5,DDew<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=7174</ref> ||\n|-\n| Darrou || ''c.'' 470 || - ||\n|-\n|}\n\n===Ecology===\n--------------------------------\nThe range forms part of the Silver Flowe-Merrick Kells Biosphere Reserve, which incorporates a considerable portion of both ranges to the west and east, and is a [[Natura 2000]] site. <ref>https://eunis.eea.europa.eu/sites/UK0019841</ref> The area is very popular with invertebrates and swarms of [[Odonata]], [[Syrphidae]] and [[Lepidoptera]] during summer are common. <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver_Flowe-Merrick_Kells</ref> The main lochs attributed to the range are Loch Dungeon, Loch Minnoch and Loch Harrow, all on the east side and in close proximity. Loch Dungeon was known to historically contain [[Arctic Charr]] which died out due to acidification; [[Brown trout]] populations, however, survived and the water quality has improved. <ref>https://www.gallowayfisheriestrust.org/charr-Loch-Grannoch.php</ref> There are currently ten [[Osprey]] pairs known to nest in [[Dumfries and Galloway]]; these lochs are a known feeding ground. <ref>https://www.wwt.org.uk/wetland-centres/caerlaverock/experience/ospreys/#</ref><ref>http://www.gsabiosphere.org.uk/supporters/loch-doon-ospreys/</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\n--------------------------------\n'Rhinns' derives from the [[Old Irish]] ''rind'', later [[Ulster Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]] ''rinn'', meaning 'promontory' or 'point'. <ref>https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/rinn#Irish</ref> [[Kells, Dumfries and Galloway|'Kells']] is a parish in the historic county of [[Kirkcudbrightshire|Stewartry of Kirkcudbright]] to the southeast of the range near [[New Galloway]]. Its name possibly derives from the Old Irish ''cell'', later Irish and Scottish Gaelic ''cill'', meaning 'church', <ref>Blackie C (1887). A dictionary of place-names giving their derivations. Murray: London.</ref> but may instead be in reference to its heightened elevation or, historically, wooded land. <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kells,_Dumfries_and_Galloway</ref> Most of the hill names are of Scottish Gaelic or [[Scots language|Scots]] origin, such as Meikle (Scots: ''large'') Millyea (Scottish Gaelic: grey, round hill - ''meall liath''), which translates fully to 'large, grey, round hill'. <ref>https://www.screel.co.uk/walks/dumfries-galloway/the-rhinns-of-hell/</ref>\n\n===References===\n--------------------------------\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of the Southern Uplands]]\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category: Mountains and hills of East Ayrshire]]\n", "name_user": "Iangpark", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhinns_of_Kells"}
{"title_page": "Scarborough Centre (electoral district)", "text_new": "{{about||the provincial electoral district|Scarborough Centre (provincial electoral district)|the subway station and bus terminal|Scarborough Centre (TTC)|and|Scarborough Centre Bus Terminal}}\n\n{{Infobox Canada electoral district\n| name = Scarborough Centre \n| province            = Ontario\n| image               = Scarborough Centre in relation to the other Toronto ridings (2015 boundaries).png\n| caption             = Scarborough Centre in relation to the other Toronto ridings (2013 boundaries) \n| coordinates         = {{coord|43.753|N|79.273|W|display=inline,title}}\n| fed-status          = active\n| fed-district-number = 35094\n| fed-created         = 1976\n| fed-abolished       = \n| fed-election-first  = 1979\n| fed-election-last   = 2019\n| fed-rep             = Salma Zahid\n| fed-rep-link        = \n| fed-rep-party       = Liberal\n| fed-rep-party-link  = Liberal Party of Canada\n| demo-pop-ref        = <ref>[[#2011fed|Statistics Canada]]: 2011</ref>\n| demo-area-ref       = <ref>[[#2011fed|Statistics Canada]]: 2011</ref>\n| demo-electors-ref   = \n| demo-census-date    = [[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]\n| demo-pop            = 108826\n| demo-electors       = 70145\n| demo-electors-date  = 2015\n| demo-area           = 30\n| demo-cd             = [[Toronto]]\n| demo-csd            = [[Toronto]]\n}}\n[[Image:Scarborough Centre Elections Canada map 35094 (2015 boundaries).gif|thumb|250px|right|Map of Scarborough Centre]]\n\n'''Scarborough Centre''' ({{lang-fr|'''Scarborough-Centre'''}}) is a federal [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] in [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], that has been represented in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] since 1979.\n\nThe riding was created in 1976 from parts of [[Scarborough East]], [[Scarborough West]] and [[York\u2014Scarborough]] ridings.\n\nIt consists of the part of the [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]] district of the City of [[Toronto]] bounded:\n*on the west by Victoria Park Avenue,\n*on the north by Highway 401,\n*on the east by McCowan Road, Lawrence Avenue East and Bellamy Road North, and\n*on the south by Eglinton Avenue East.\n\nNotable landmarks in Scarborough Centre include:\n* [[Scarborough Civic Centre]], site of east [[Toronto]] district council meetings, and adjacent [[Albert Campbell Square]]\n* [[Scarborough Town Centre]], a large shopping mall\n* [[Scarborough Centre (TTC)|Scarborough Centre]] [[Scarborough RT|RT]] station\n* [[Scarborough Hospital]], General Division\n* [[Scarborough Historical Museum]]\n\nIt has been represented in the House of Commons by Liberal MP [[Salma Zahid]] since 2015.\n\n==Geography==\nThe riding contains the neighbourhoods of [[Scarborough City Centre]] (west of McCowan Road), [[Bendale]] (west of McCowan and south of Lawrence), [[Eglinton East]], [[Ionview]] (north of Eglinton Avenue), [[Golden Mile, Toronto|Golden Mile]] (north of Eglinton Avenue), [[Wexford, Toronto|Wexford]], [[Maryvale, Toronto|Maryvale]], and [[Dorset Park]].\n\n==History==\n\nScarborough Centre was created in 1976. It consisted initially of the part of the Borough of Scarborough bounded on the west by Victoria Park Avenue, on the north by Ellesmere Road, on the east by Bellamy Road North, and on the south by Eglinton Avenue East.\n\nIn 1987, it was expanded to include the part of Scarborough lying bounded by Bellamy Road North, Lawrence Avenue East, Markham Road and Eglinton Avenue East.\n\nIn 1996, it was redefined such that it was bounded:\n* on the west by Victoria Park Avenue,\n*on the north by a line drawn from west to east along Ellesmere Road, north along the Canadian National Railway and west along Highway 401,\n* on the east by a line drawn from north to south along Highland Creek East, west along Ellesmere Road, south along Scarborough Golf Club Road, west along Lawrence Avenue East and south along Markham Road, and\n*on the south by Eglinton Avenue East.\n\nIn 2003, it was given its current boundaries as described above.\n\nThis riding lost territory to [[Scarborough\u2014Guildwood]], and gained territory from [[Scarborough Southwest]] during the [[Canadian federal electoral redistribution, 2012|2012 electoral redistribution]].\n\n===Members of Parliament===\n\nThis riding has elected the following [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]]:\n\n{{CanMP|}}\n{{CanMP nodata|Scarborough Centre<br />''Riding created from'' [[Scarborough East]], [[Scarborough West]]<br>''and'' [[York\u2014Scarborough]]}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1979\n| ToYr = 1980\n| Assembly# = 31\n| CanParty = PC\n| RepName = Diane Stratas\n| RepTerms# = 1\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1980\n| ToYr = 1984\n| Assembly# = 32\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = Norm Kelly\n| RepTerms# = 1\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1984\n| ToYr = 1988\n| Assembly# = 33\n| CanParty = PC\n| RepName = Pauline Browes\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1988\n| ToYr = 1993\n| Assembly# = 34\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1993\n| ToYr = 1997\n| Assembly# = 35\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = John Cannis\n| RepTerms# = 6\n| PartyTerms# = 6\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1997\n| ToYr = 2000\n| Assembly# = 36\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2000\n| ToYr = 2004\n| Assembly# = 37\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2004\n| ToYr = 2006\n| Assembly# = 38\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2006\n| ToYr = 2008\n| Assembly# = 39\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2008\n| ToYr = 2011\n| Assembly# = 40\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2011\n| ToYr = 2015\n| Assembly# = 41\n| CanParty = Conservative\n| RepName = Roxanne James\n| RepTerms# = 1\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2015\n| ToYr = 2019\n| Assembly# = 42\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = Salma Zahid\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2019\n| ToYr = \n| Assembly# = 43\n}}\n{{CanMP end}}\n\n==Former boundaries==\n<gallery>\nImage:Scarborough Centre, 1976.png|1976 to 19